Tested on Copter v4.6.3 and v4.7.0-beta1

Note that this project only commands the drone to move at a specified velocity and yaw at programmed yaw rates 
to avoid obstacles and navigate the environment. 
Any other behaviour of the drone will have to be configured by the user and does not necessarily depend on this script.

Hardware Requirements
---------------------
    - ArduPilot drone
    - RGB Camera (This project uses an ESP32-CAM)
    - Link to wirelessly send camera frames to GCS
    - Wireless telemetry link (ESP32, ESP8266, SiK radio, etc)
    - Optical Flow sensor for indoor pose estimation
    - Onboard compass (magnetometer) for heading estimation
    - Optional: GPS can be used instead of optical flow if used outdoors (outdoor flight is untested)

Firmware Configuration
----------------------
    - YOU NEED TO SETUP AND TUNE THE DRONE AS DOCUMENTED AT https://ardupilot.org/copter/docs/initial-setup.html or use 
      the ArduPilot Methodic Configurator - https://github.com/ArduPilot/MethodicConfigurator
    
    - Setup the vehicle to use optical flow indoors. Either optical flow or GPS works outside (but not tested)
      Optical flow setup: https://ardupilot.org/copter/docs/common-optical-flow-sensors-landingpage.html
                          https://ardupilot.org/copter/docs/common-optical-flow-sensor-setup.html
    
    - Setup all failsafes. GCS and RC failsafes are especially important. If you don't plan on using an RC, it's 
      recommended to setup a joystick in case you want to take over manual control after easily switching to a manual mode.
    
    # - Recommended to set EK3_USE_RNG_HGT so that the rangefinder is used below this percentage of its specified 
    #   maximum altitude range. This will prevent noisy barometer altitude messing up the reconstruction.

    - Terrain should probably be disabled for indoor flight, but you can experiment with it for outdoor flight. If enabled, make sure to set the 
      appropriate parameters.
